About Blue Rondo a la Turk\
\

\b0 Blue Rondo a la Turk is a jazz composition written by Dave Brubeck. It\'92s composed in 9/8 meter, with a solo section in 4/4 (swing) time. Western time signatures consists of two numerals. The lower number represents the beat unit, and the top number indicates beats per bar. This song is interesting in the unusual rhythmic patterns that it employs. 
\fs28 \cf2 \cb3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Brubeck first heard this unusual rhythm performed by Turkish musicians on the street. Upon asking the musicians where they got the rhythm, one replied,\
\
"This rhythm is to us what the blues is to you."\
\
The first third of the piece consists of seven different sections. Each section has four measures. The first three measures divide the 9 counts per beat into the following pattern: 2+2+2+3. This is sometimes known as additive or compound time signature. The fourth measure divides the measure in thirds: 3+3+3. The cycle then repeats.\
\
The first five sections are 4 measures in length, but repeat twice. The final two sections are 8 measures in length, making a total of 56. The pattern changes in the last two sections, from three groups of 2+2+2+3 to four groupings.\
\
After the first third, the 9/8 time is alternated with 4/4 time (what jazz musicians call \'93trading fours\'94) and then the 4/4 time sticks on a standard 12-bar blues pattern. Alto saxophonist Paul Desmond and Brubeck both play solos over the rhythm section of 
\fs26\fsmilli13300 Joe Morello on drums and Eugene Wright on bass.\
\
After the solo sections, the 4/4/ time is alternated with 9/8 again. This leads a to a reprise of the seven sections from the beginning and ending in a slowing tempo (
\i molto rallentando
\i0 ) coda. \
\
Blue Rondo a la Turk is not just famous for the unique mechanics and structure underlying the composition, but also for its cultural impact. The flip side of the single \'93Take Five\'94, it was the first jazz single to sell more than a million copies and became the best selling single of 1960. Brubeck played the song for decades and it has became a standard in the jazz playbook. 
