Creative Process\
\

\b0 Visualizing Blue Rondo a la turk began with simple proportions. The main rhythmic pattern of 2+2+2+3 seemed to be easily translated to boxes. Begin with a length, and divide by 3. Take the first of the two thirds and divide that length by 3 to show the pattern of the two counts. This results in 4 squares that occupy areas equal to the values of the counts per beat. \
\
It became clear that the repeating cycle of three \'932+2+2+3\'94 bars followed by a fourth \'933+3+3\'94 should be laid out in four quadrants. I renamed the \'932+2+2+3\'94 pattern as an \'93A\'94 type and the \'933+3+3\'94 as a \'93B\'94 type. In my code and designs, I referred to these as \'93A\'94 compositions and \'93B\'94 compositions or comps. So, a full repeating section would consist of 3 \'93A\'94s, randomly assigned followed by one \'93B\'94 also drawn from a pool of possible comps.\
\
I stared at the album cover of Time Out and began sampling and referencing the 1959 design. I sampled and blocked out the colors from the typography used on the cover, and used an updated gothic typeface in my interface mockups. \
\
I became curious about the painting, and found that the designer and the painter were one and the same: S. Neil Fujita. I I began modernizing and referencing the cover painting in my graphics as I began to expand out the pools of \'93A\'94 and \'93B\'94 comps. After some research into S. Neil Fujita, I inevitably was attracted to many of his other designs from the period, such as the covers for Fortune magazine and other album cover art for Columbia records. Much of the visual language of Fujita is found in the visualizations in blueron.do.\
\
While this seemed relatively straightforward, translating time to space seemed limiting in a time based medium. \
